Design an articulated object by writing `src/design.json` — a frozen, machine-readable contract that every downstream task will read. **Output ONLY the JSON file via the Write tool. No commentary, no markdown fences.**

## What to build

{{ prompt }}

If reference image(s) are provided in the workspace (`prompts/references/`), Read them and let them guide the parts, proportions, colors, and style.

## Required schema (no comments, no trailing commas)

```
{
  "robot_name": "<machine-readable slug>",
  "description": "<one-line natural language description>",
  "parts": [
    {
      "name": "<PascalCase>",                       // matches bpy.data.objects key + URDF link name
      "role": "<one-line natural language role>",
      "geometry_strategy": "<advisory; e.g. 5-panel-join | bmesh-boolean | extruded-bar | D-handle | recessed-pull>",
      "world_xyz": [cx, cy, cz],                    // bbox CENTER in world coords (meters)
      "world_extents": [w, d, h],                   // full size along X / Y / Z (meters, positive)
      "color_rgba": [r, g, b, a],
      // Optional: "place_method": "baked" (default) | "canonical".
      //   baked: part built at world position; world_xyz is bbox center after build_<part>().
      //   canonical: part built at origin; build.py applies world_xyz + world_rpy after construction.
      //   Use "canonical" when (a) the part should be reusable across projects, or (b) the
      //   pipeline will later re-render at multiple joint poses (e.g. drawer 0/50/100% open).
      //   Default to "baked" unless one of those reasons applies.
      // Optional per-part sub-specs:
      "cavity": { "world_xyz": [...], "world_extents": [...], "open_axis": "<axis>" },
      "wall_thickness": <meters>,
      "outer_bevel_radius": <meters>,
      "front_inset_depth": <meters>,
      "front_inset_margin": <meters>,
      // Optional template-and-instances. When the prompt's "TEMPLATE PARTS"
      // section lists this part, you MUST include an `instances` array here.
      // build.py constructs the canonical mesh once via build_<lower>() then
      // copies + applies each entry's transform, producing N scene objects
      // named <PascalName>_0..<PascalName>_{N-1}. world_xyz / world_extents
      // describe ONE canonical instance, not the cluster.
      "instances": [
        {"rotation_euler": [rx, ry, rz]},                              // rotation only (radians)
        {"rotation_euler": [rx, ry, rz], "translation": [tx, ty, tz]}, // both
        {"translation": [tx, ty, tz]}                                  // translation only (meters)
      ],
      // Texture spec — IMAGE GENERATION IS THE DEFAULT. Set a short `prompt`
      // describing the material; the framework generates a tileable PNG (Gemini
      // Nano Banana) and the build harness UV-unwraps + binds it automatically.
      // Geometry code NEVER touches texture — you author the look here, in
      // design.json, and nowhere else. The PNG path is derived automatically
      // (src/textures/<part_name>.png); do NOT specify it. Give EVERY part a
      // `texture.prompt` unless you deliberately want it left flat (then omit
      // the whole `texture` block and it renders in `color_rgba`).
      "texture": {
        "prompt": "<image-gen prompt for the material, e.g. 'seamless tileable brushed aluminium, fine linear grain, matte, 4k'>",
        "material_hint": "<optional one-line material cue, e.g. 'matte black rubber'>"
      }
    }
    // ... more parts
  ],
  "joints": [
    {
      "name": "<joint_name>",
      "type": "<prismatic | revolute | fixed | continuous>",
      "parent": "<PascalCase part name>",
      "child":  "<PascalCase part name>",
      "axis":   [x, y, z],                          // only for non-fixed joints
      "limit_from_rest": [lower, upper]              // only for prismatic / revolute. Joint position 0 == rest pose.
    }
    // ... more joints
  ]
}
```

## TEMPLATE PARTS — what to look for in prompt

If the prompt above contains a `## TEMPLATE PARTS` section like:

```
## TEMPLATE PARTS
- Leg: 4 instances; translation=[(+0.15,+0.15,0),(+0.15,-0.15,0),(-0.15,+0.15,0),(-0.15,-0.15,0)]
- FanBlade: 6 instances; rotation_euler=[(0,0,0),(0,1.047,0),(0,2.094,0),(0,3.142,0),(0,4.189,0),(0,5.236,0)]
```

… each listed part in `design.json` MUST include the `instances` array (schema above). Translate each tuple from prompt into a dict in the array:

- `translation=[(+0.15,+0.15,0),(+0.15,-0.15,0),...]` becomes `"instances": [{"translation":[0.15,0.15,0]}, {"translation":[0.15,-0.15,0]}, ...]`
- `rotation_euler=[(0,0,0),(0,1.047,0),...]` becomes `"instances": [{"rotation_euler":[0,0,0]}, {"rotation_euler":[0,1.047,0]}, ...]`

For template parts, set `world_xyz` / `world_extents` to describe **ONE canonical instance** (e.g. one leg's bbox, not the four legs combined). The canonical anchor is typically the origin or one of the instance positions — pick whichever makes the canonical build_<lower>() simplest.

If the prompt has NO `## TEMPLATE PARTS` section, do NOT add `instances` anywhere — every part is single-instance.

## Sanity checks before writing

- The `joints` form ONE connected tree spanning every part: each pair of adjacent parts connects via a single joint, and every non-root part has exactly one parent joint (the root part is implicit). A *static* object is NOT an empty joints array — it is this same tree with every joint `type: "fixed"`. A jointless / multi-root design exports a degenerate URDF.
- Connected parts fit with the stated clearance — e.g. a drawer's bbox plus the joint's allowed range must fit within its parent cavity's extents minus the design's clearance
- Rest pose is what gets RENDERED — choose it so the articulation is visible (e.g. drawer half-open, door slightly ajar) unless the prompt says otherwise
- All `world_extents` are positive
- `axis` is a unit vector (or close enough)
- Joint origins implied by the parts' `world_xyz` (the framework will compute them from the design)
- Coords: meters, Z up. The "front" axis is whichever direction the spec calls "the front"

Use the Write tool to create `src/design.json`. Output valid JSON only.
